matchAny

public final <T> Boolean matchAny(Collection<T> queryMetrics,
                                  Collection<T> subjectMetrics)
Simple collection matching method determines whether there is any union between the two collections. If the collection objects are not primitives should override the equals/hashCode methods. For optimal performance a HashSet would work best with this method.

Parameters:
queryMetrics - collection of query metrics
subjectMetrics - collection of subject metrics
Returns:
whether these is any match between the two sets

matchMetric

public Boolean matchMetric(M queryMetric,
                           M subjectMetric)
Default metric matching uses the Object.equals() method of the query metric to determine weather the two calculated metrics are equals. You would normally want to override this default behaviour particularly when dealing with collections. If the calculated metric is a Collection then the matchAny(java.util.Collection, java.util.Collection) and matchAll(java.util.Collection, java.util.Collection) provide some default collection matching.

Please not this method is not null safe and parsing a null object as the queryMetric will throw a null pointer exception.

Specified by:
matchMetric in interface EntityMatcher<E extends Entity,M>
Parameters:
queryMetric - calculated query metric
subjectMetric - calculated subject metric
Returns:
whether the metrics match

partialMatch

public Boolean partialMatch()
Description copied from interface: EntityMatcher
Indicates if the match is partial. Partial matches can not be optimised in a map. In most case a matcher will look for exact matches and thus this method should return false. Partial matches are useful if we are looking to reference example at sub-structures/generic structures.

Specified by:
partialMatch in interface EntityMatcher<E extends Entity,M>
